**Code Explanation:**

The code generates two multi-panel figures to visualize the performance of the SR-DAE model and assess its scientific validity. 1. Map Comparison Figure: It loads the ground truth tSZ maps, the raw SO-LAT 150 GHz observations (converted to Compton-y units for direct comparison), and the SR-DAE reconstructed maps for the first 50 patches. It selects the 3 patches with the highest integrated tSZ signal to serve as representative examples. The figure displays these patches side-by-side, sharing a consistent color scale (vmin and vmax) per row to highlight the model's denoising and component separation capabilities. 2. Performance Assessment Figure: This figure contains four panels: - Panel A (Radial Power Spectra): Computes and compares the mean radial power spectrum (C_l) of the ground truth and reconstructed maps across the 50 patches, demonstrating how well the spatial frequencies are recovered. - Panel B (Cross-correlation): Plots the cross-correlation coefficient (r_l) between the reconstruction and ground truth for both the standard test set and the CIB-shuffled null test, verifying that the model learns physical correlations rather than hallucinating features. - Panel C (Y_SZ - Mass Relation): Displays a scatter plot of the integrated reconstructed Y_SZ versus the ground truth mass proxy, comparing the SR-DAE output against the raw SO-LAT data to show the reduction in variance. - Panel D (Residual Scatter): Plots the standard deviation of the residuals across different mass bins for the standard reconstruction, null test, and raw data. A logarithmic y-axis is used because the scatter spans several orders of magnitude. Finally, the script prints a concise summary of the key statistics (power spectra values, cross-correlation coefficients, and residual scatter) to the console so the researcher agent can interpret the quantitative results. All units are dimensionless (Compton-y parameter and its derivatives).

**Modifications:**

Added the required if __name__ == '__main__': block, ensured all paths use the data/ directory, and verified that no LaTeX rendering is used in the plots or print statements.

